  <p>Abstract: Since Kratzer‚Äôs (2006) seminal work, the conjecture that embedded that-clauses denote predicates of contentful entities has been a recurring theme in the literature on attitude ascriptions. In this seminar, I‚Äôll outline a particular take on this idea from Elliott (2018), which marries Kratzer‚Äôs semantics for embedded that-clauses with a neo-Davidsonian semantics for attitude verbs. We‚Äôll discuss some concrete linguistic arguments for this world view, and relate it to the broad philosophical literature on substitution failures (Prior 1971, a.o.).</p>

